    name: "Hôtel Particulier Montmartre",
    description: `Hidden behind an unmarked door on the Allée des Brouillards in the bohemian village of Montmartre, Hôtel Particulier is Paris's most artistically extraordinary secret. This private 19th-century mansion — once the atelier and home of Hermès heir Frédéric Dumas — has been transformed into a five-suite hotel that blurs the boundary between luxury accommodation and living contemporary art installation.

Each of the five suites has been entirely conceptualised and executed by a different internationally acclaimed artist, resulting in spaces unlike anything else in hospitality. One suite is dominated by a hand-painted ceiling mural of tangled botanical specimens; another is draped floor-to-ceiling in vintage Aubusson tapestries sourced from Burgundy châteaux. All suites feature private gardens or terraces — an almost unimaginable luxury in central Paris — where breakfast is served beneath wisteria-draped pergolas. Original artworks hang throughout the property, and the curated collection rotates annually.

The hidden cocktail bar, Le Très Particulier, is perhaps the finest clandestine drinking establishment in Paris. Accessed through the garden, it attracts a devoted following of Parisian intellectuals, artists, and musicians who come for the extraordinary gin programme, the live jazz on Friday evenings, and the legendary sangria punches served in crystal bowls. Breakfast — featuring freshly baked croissants from the nearby Arnaud Delmontel bakery, seasonal fruit compotes, and hand-pressed juices — is the perfect intimate start to a Parisian morning.

The hotel offers an unparalleled programme of curated Montmartre experiences: private tours of the Musée de Montmartre with the curator, early-morning oil-painting classes on the Butte with a resident artist, evenings at the Lapin Agile cabaret, and bespoke itineraries to discover the neighbourhood's hidden studios, vintage bookshops, and wine caves.`,
